          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>A field in Kyiv oblast, Ukraine, where a British charity cleared landmines in 2022. Credits: Chris Strickland for The Telegraph/Halo Trust
          </i></p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Poland and the Baltic states, Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania, announced plans to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-03-2025-h1-1-withdraw-from-the-ottawa-treaty?source=website" target="_blank">withdraw from the Ottawa Treaty</a>, which bans anti-personnel landmines. The announcement comes amid growing threats from Russia and Belarus. In a joint statement, their defense ministers said the security situation has “significantly deteriorated” since signing the treaty. They said it is “paramount” to ensure flexibility in defending NATO’s eastern flank.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">The Ottawa Treaty, signed by over 160 countries, took effect in 1997 to ban mines targeting humans. However, Russia, China, the US, and others never signed. Despite exiting the treaty, the four pledged commitment to international humanitarian law and ensuring civilians' protection during the conflict. All four countries are in the NATO alliance and share borders with Russia.
       </p>
        </mj-text>
